    "86348741": {
      "title": "Evaluation of commercial phytase enzymes on performance and tibia-breaking strength of male broiler chicks",
      "abstract": "SUMMARY An experiment was conducted to evaluate the effects of 3 commercial phytase enzymes on the performance and bone strength of broilers. All birds were fed a corn-soybean meal diet (22% CP, 3,086 kcal/kg) adequate in all nutrients but nonphytate P (npP) through 28 d of age. Dietary treatments were created using 3 npP levels (0.25, 0.35, and 0.45%, designated low, marginal, and standard, respectively), and 3 commercially available phytase enzymes (A, B, and C) were supplemented in diets containing 0.25% npP. Individual BW and group feed consumption were recorded weekly and feed:gain (corrected for mortality) was calculated weekly. Each week, 24 birds per treatment were slaughtered for tibia collection to evaluate bone strength. Supplementation of the low-npP diet with phytase A or C improved BW, feed consumption, and tibia-breaking strength so that it was similar (P > 0.05) to birds fed the standard-npP diet, whereas supplementing birds with phytase B led to BW, feed consumption, and bone strength closely resembling those of birds fed marginal npP. Feed efficiency was not significantly affected (P > 0.05) by phytase supplementation in comparison with the low-npP or standard-npP treatments. Mortality was significantly decreased with phytase supplementation, regardless of the specific source, in comparison with the low-npP treatment, on conclusion of the experiment. We conclude, given the conditions of this experiment, that broiler performance and bone mineralization are improved when dietary npP is reduced by a minimum of 0.10% and when phytase supplementation is used."
    }
